iged leave still fixed residence country coterie insisted motive pure obstinacy weary even death retirement eaten pride chose rather become victim stubbornness recover return paris letter d alembert breathed gentleness mind which every one perceived affected been dissatisfied retreat style manner borne evident marks ill humor reigned all works written paris first wrote country least appearance found persons who knew how distinguish remark decisive perceived returned element yet same work notwithstanding all mildness breathed made mistake own usual ill luck another enemy amongst men letters become acquainted marmontel house m de la popliniere his acquaintance been continued baron marmontel time wrote mercure de france too much pride send works authors periodical publications wishing send without his imagining consequence title being desirous should speak mercure wrote upon book author mercure m marmontel thought paid fine compliment mistook cruel offence became irreconcilable enemy wrote against letter politeness true bitterness easily perceptible since time never lost opportunity injuring society indirectly ill treating his works such difficulty there managing irritable self love men letters careful ought every person leave anything equivocal compliments pay having nothing more disturb took advantage leisure independence continue literary pursuits more coherence winter finished eloisa sent rey who printed year following however interrupted projects circumstance sufficiently disagreeable heard new preparations making opera house give devin du village enraged seeing these people arrogantly dispose property again took memoir sent m d argenson which no answer been returned having made some trifling alterations sent manuscript m sellon resident geneva letter which pleased charge himself comte de st florentin who succeeded m d argenson opera department duclos whom communicated what done mentioned petits violons who offered restore opera freedom theatre which no longer sit