ess manage better lass turned ran part house leaving us alone together alan high good humour furthering his schemes bitter dudgeon being called jacobite treated like child alan cried stand no more ye ll sit davie said if ye upset pot now ye may scrape own life fire alan breck dead man true only groan even groan served alan s purpose overheard lass came flying again dish white puddings bottle strong ale poor lamb says no sooner set meat before us touched shoulder little friendly touch much bid cheer told us fall there no more pay inn own least father s gone day pittencrieff waited no second bidding bread cheese cold comfort puddings smelt excellently well while sat ate took same place next table looking thinking frowning herself drawing string apron through hand m thinking ye rather long tongue said last alan ay said alan ye see ken folk speak never betray ye said if ye mean no said ye re kind ll tell ye what ye ye help couldnae said shaking head na couldnae no said if ye answered nothing look here lass said alan there boats kingdom fife saw two no less upon beach came town s end now if use boat pass cloud night lothian some secret decent kind man bring boat back again keep his counsel there two souls saved mine all likelihood his dead surety if lack boat three shillings left wide world where go how what other place there us except chains gibbet give naked word kenna shall go wanting lassie ye lie warm bed think upon us when wind gowls chimney rain tirls roof ye eat meat cheeks red fire think upon poor sick lad mine biting his finger ends blae muir cauld hunger sick sound must aye moving death grapple his throat must aye trailing rain lang roads when gants his last rickle cauld stanes there nae friends near only god appeal see lass great trouble mind being tempted help us yet some fear might helping malefactors now determined step myself allay scruples portion truth ever hear said mr rankeillor ferry rankeillor writer said daur say well said s his door am bound may j